<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / Campbell aims to clinch third Conservative term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OTTAWA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADA's ruling Progressive Conservative party last night chose Ms Kim
Campbell as its leader and the country's first woman prime minister.
Ms Campbell, a blunt-speaking 46-year-old lawyer from Vancouver, won against
four other candidates on the second ballot of a party convention in Ottawa.
She secured 53 per cent of the votes cast by 3,452 delegates on the final
ballot. Her nearest rival was Mr Jean Charest, the environment minister. The
other three candidates withdrew after the first ballot.
Ms Campbell had originally been regarded as a firm favourite to win the
contest because of her credentials as a bilingual woman candidate from
British Columbia. But her lead narrowed before the convention after she was
characterised as a prickly intellectual whose command of French was not as
fluent as first thought.
Ms Campbell, currently defence minister, will take over from Mr Brian
Mulroney and announce a new cabinet within 10 days.
Her immediate priority is to secure a third consecutive mandate for the
Conservatives in the next general election, which a senior party official
said would probably be called in September. The Conservatives and the
opposition Liberals are running neck-and-neck in opinion polls.
Ms Campbell, who was hailed during the convention as 'a new sensation' in
Canadian politics, indicated that she would try to distance herself from the
record of the unpopular Mulroney government, without making any radical
changes in policy.
In her keynote speech, she promised 'a new agenda for government and a new
approach to politics'. She pledged 'not to duck our problems but to confront
them'. But she has given few specifics, beyond a commitment to eliminate the
federal budget deficit, which totalled close to CDollars 35bn (Pounds
17.8bn) last year, within five years. She also pledged to 'reduce the size
and scale of government'.
Ms Campbell has backed the North American Free Trade Agreement between the
US, Canada and Mexico. A senior adviser said yesterday, however, that her
early initiatives may include an adjustment programme to help workers whose
jobs are threatened.
</TEXT>
