FT  14 JUN 93 / Observer: Low life
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Time was when being a life president meant something. In return for giving
up the keys to the chairman's suite, corporate grandees were rewarded with a
title, secretaries, free lunches and continued use of chauffeur-driven
limos.
But outgoing Hammerson chairman Sydney Mason, one of the grand old men of
British property, is not even being allowed to keep his office when he
inherits his title after Hammerson's annual meeting today. Indeed, he will
be lucky if he can even find his name in future annual reports.
How he must envy Lord King, British Airways' newly created president. One of
the rumoured perks of being an ex-chairman of a big airline is a lifetime's
free flying on any of the world's main airlines.
