<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / ITV options reach Brooke today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT will today be offered a range of options for relaxing the
rules on ITV ownership.
Mr Peter Brooke, the heritage secretary, will meet the chairmen of the 14
regional ITV companies to hear whether there is a case for lifting the ban
on the nine largest ITV companies taking each other over.
The five largest companies are all expected to argue for a relaxation -
something that will equally be opposed by middle-ranking broadcasters such
as HTV and Anglia which do not want to be swallowed by their larger ITV
rivals.
Mr Leslie Hill, chairman of Central Independent Television, who has been
campaigning for the freedom to create a smaller number of more substantial
ITV companies, will present four alternatives.
He will argue that one large company should be able either to own:
ITV licences controlling up to 25 per cent of the ITV advertising market.
Up to 25 per cent of the total television advertising market including
Channel 4, breakfast and satellite.
One other large company.
Under a fourth alternative, Mr Hill believes there could be a redefining of
what is considered a large company.
He said yesterday: 'For a single channel to be run by a minimum of nine
companies has got to be absurd.' Apart from unnecessary duplication he
pointed to the 'pathetically long time' it took to get decisions in such a
federal system.
Mr Michael Green, chairman of Carlton Communications, will back up his
campaign for a relaxation of rules with a Carlton paper arguing that Pounds
100m a year could be saved by ending unnecessary duplication in areas such
as administration.
HTV and Anglia, supported by Lord Hollick, chairman of Meridian
Broadcasting, the south of England ITV company, will vehemently oppose any
piecemeal change in the rules. They will argue that concentration of
ownership in ITV will mean less regional diversity, less competition and
less network production in the regions.
The middle-ranking companies will also emphasise that no ITV company is
about to fail - in spite of increased sums going to the Treasury - so that
there is no need for immediate intervention.
The fact that ITV is hopelessly split on the ownership issue will probably
make it less likely that Mr Brooke will decide to change the provisions of
the 1990 Broadcasting Act so soon after their implementation.
</TEXT>
