<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / Row with generators threatens 12 pits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOUBTS ABOUT the future of 12 reprieved coal mines have increased following
the insistence by the two main electricity generators that British Coal cut
prices below world levels to reflect stocking costs.
'There is no reason why our shareholders should have to pay stocking costs
for coal we do not need immediately,' said an executive of one generator.
The hardline approach by National Power and PowerGen will anger ministers
because the government has said it will subsidise output from the 12 to meet
the difference between production costs and sale prices.
Unless British Coal can increase sales by 15m tonnes a year it is likely to
have to start closing the pits. They were reprieved less than two months ago
after a public outcry over ministers' plans for further sharp contraction of
the mining industry.
The generators' case for lower prices is based on their argument that
anything they buy will have to be added to stockpiles already big enough to
meet the needs of power stations for six months.
British Coal has already negotiated to sell 40m tonnes of coal to the
generators this year and 30m in each of the next four years.
These sales will, however, provide a market for only the 19 pits which
British Coal considers its core mines. With extra sales to household and
industrial markets looking limited, the generators are British Coal's main
hope for sustaining the 12 reprieved pits.
The company has already offered to cut the price to between 90p and 95p a
gigajoule - a measure of thermal efficiency - less than two thirds the price
in the core contracts.
But that figure compares with a price of about 86p for coal traded in
Rotterdam, where most coal imports to Europe are bought and sold.
Neither PowerGen nor National Power is likely to make any final decisions on
extra purchases before serious negotiations begin between them and British
Coal in the autumn. At these negotiations the generators are likely to
insist on prices lower than 80p.
Some British Coal executives believe the company will have to struggle to
sell even 8m additional tonnes a year to the generators. That makes closures
among the 12 almost inevitable.
In a white paper on coal in March this year, the government promised
subsidies for output from the 12 but was unspecific about how they should be
paid and on what basis they should be calculated. Negotiations between
British Coal and the government on the subsidies are at a preliminary stage.
On the day the white paper was published, Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, indicated that up to Pounds 500m would be available for
subsidies.
</TEXT>
