<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / BSI chief resigns in 'disagreement'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL SANDERSON, first chief executive of the British Standards
Institution, has resigned unexpectedly after 18 months. The BSI co-ordinates
the writing of standards for industry.
Mr Sanderson's resignation, which took effect on June 1 but has only now
emerged, followed what the BSI called 'a deep disagreement with the board on
important matters of policy and management'.
He joined BSI from AWD Bedford Trucks, where he had been managing director.
'I am very sad,' he said. 'It was a wonderful job. I think we were making
significant progress.'
A metallurgist by training, Mr Sanderson, who is now 49, was appointed in
November 1991 to spearhead the modernisation of the organisation. The BSI
said at the time that his task would be to 'lead a major programme of
cultural change'. His departure leaves the organisation without a chief
executive at a time of growing interest in the issue of standards.
BS5750, a quality systems standard, has become the focus of growing
controversy with criticism from small businesses that it is unduly
bureaucratic while the creation of the single European market has increased
the need for a strong British voice in the writing of European and
international standards.
Neither the BSI nor Mr Sanderson would comment further on the reasons for
his departure. Mr Sanderson was on a renewable 12-month contract.
Day-to-day management of BSI has been taken over by a three-man board
committee headed by Mr Vivian Thomas, non-executive chairman. He said:
'There is no question of any change of strategic emphasis and we will pursue
our objectives with the utmost vigour.'
