<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / MPs demand copier leases change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CAMPAIGN to extend greater protection to customers of controversial
photocopying leasing contracts will be stepped up tomorrow when a group of
MPs meets Baroness Denton, consumer affairs minister, to press for changes
in the law.
The photocopying business has been the target of widespread allegations
about high-pressure sales techniques which have led many businesses and
organisations to sign onerous and unfair leasing contracts.
The Office of Fair Trading announced in February, in response to more than
3,000 complaints of malpractice and contract abuse, that it was launching an
inquiry into the hiring and leasing of office equipment.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, has also just
submitted to the Department of Trade and Industry the initial conclusions of
a review of the Consumer Credit Act 1974.
He is believed to have told the department that, among other measures to
improve consumer law, there is a case for widening the legal protection
available on contracts involving private individuals to small businesses and
other incorporated bodies.
Changes could mean that bodies such as schools, hospitals, clubs and
charities - all of which have alleged being tricked into expensive contracts
 -would win a two-week 'cooling off' period after signing up. The present
Pounds 15,000 ceiling on such contracts could also be raised, possibly as
high as Pounds 50,000.
Companies which break the law can have their consumer credit licences
revoked by the OFT, which has warned that it will do so if it finds
evidence.
Members of the Campaign to Clean Up Photocopier Contracts, which has
gathered more than 3,300 complaints from customers - particularly those
taking out cost-per-copy-agreements - will also attend tomorrow's meeting,
which is being led by Mr Nick Hawkins, Conservative MP for Blackpool South.
A spokesman said the campaign was still receiving complaints and would
continue to press ministers for action.
Some of the leading photocopier leasing companies have responded to recent
criticism by establishing a trade association to promote good practice.
</TEXT>
