<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / Failure of computers 'may kill'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEATHS AND serious injuries caused by computer system failures are likely
within a few years unless a shortage of experienced safety engineers is
eased, the British Computer Society warned yesterday.
It said there might be more cases like that of the London Ambulance Service
unless the number of computer specialists qualified to build, inspect and
approve 'safety-critical' systems increased sharply. Poor system design and
management in the London service led to unacceptable delays in the arrival
of ambulances.
Safety-critical systems are computer systems which can lead to injuries or
deaths if they go wrong.
The London ambulance system was never declared safety-critical and was not
inspected by qualified safety experts.
Professor John Cullyer of Warwick University, chairman of a society task
force, said yesterday that computers were spreading rapidly through society.
But the training of experts in safety-critical methods was lagging behind.
He said it was impossible to put a figure on the number of extra engineers
needed, but specialists were already overstretched.
Companies qualified to carry out safety-critical inspections included
Roll-Royce, BAe-Sema, Program Validation and Thorn EMI.
Prof Cullyer, a consultant to the US space programme, said that by the turn
of the century most passenger cars would have six or more microprocessors,
at least two of them controlling potentially life-threatening functions such
as braking or suspension alignment.
Prof Cullyer said the recession in the UK had caused a sharp reduction in
training which was making the shortage worse and had serious implications
for safety over the next decade.
He said it took about 10 years for a computer engineer to gain the
experience and maturity needed to work on safety-critical systems.
Statutory regulations in the UK designed to ensure that a new computer
system passes inspection cover only the aerospace, nuclear and toxic
chemicals industries.
Defence systems are covered by rigorous standard procedures set by the
Ministry of Defence, but are not statutory.
Industries where there is no statutory requirement to have new systems
tested and approved include medical electronics, motor electronics and
manufacturing.
Prof Cullyer said a principal concern was that small companies, many of them
developing innovative and advanced systems, had neither the resources nor
incentive to ask for independent inspection of their work.
A policy statement prepared by the society's task force warns that some of
the science and technology needed to design and assess safety-critical
systems is not yet fully developed and calls on the government and the
Science and Engineering Research Council to support the necessary research
and development.
It calls for a system of registration with mandatory fault reporting for
safety-critical systems so minimum standards can be enforced.
</TEXT>
