<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / ICL faces action by ex-manager
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FORMER ICL manager, linked to an investigation into alleged irregularities
involving contracts placed with the company by the Ministry of Defence, said
he was seeking legal aid to seek compensation in the civil courts for an
alleged persecution campaign.
He said he also wanted to sue his former employer, an ICL subsidiary, for
wrongful dismissal and commission which he claims is owing.
Ministry of Defence police raided ICL's offices in Slough, Stevenage and
Basingstoke on Friday and removed documents. A ministry spokeswoman said she
could not indicate when the results of the investigation would be made
public.
Mr Richard Livesey-Haworth, ICL's group executive director, said he was
'incredulous' at the suggestion that ICL, the UK company owned by the
Japanese company Fujitsu, would persecute a former employee.
He also said that the ICL main board would have had no detailed knowledge of
the contracts in question. Contracts of the size under investigation would
be solely a matter for the subsidiary concerned and would never come before
the executive board. Only two individual contracts had been discussed by the
board in recent years, each of them multi-million pound deals.
Mr David May, formerly an MoD account manager for the ICL division ICTS, now
a wholly owned subsidiary named Workplace Technologies, said he was made
redundant after warning senior managers that the company would make
excessive profits on certain contracts. He told the FT yesterday that he had
not spoken to the ICL board.
He also said yesterday that he had subsequently made these allegations to
MoD police.
Mr May worked for the subsidiary between 1990 and 1992. It supplies cabling
and office services to customers including the ministry, whose account Mr
May handled.
Mr May said he took his story to The Sunday Times, which contacted the
ministry.
Mr Livesey-Haworth said yesterday that as the ministry had made no formal
allegations of wrongdoing it was impossible to comment on Mr May's claims.
In his opinion, however, the investigation had been instigated by 'a
disgruntled ex-employee'. ICL would continue to co-operate fully with the
investigation.
ICL was, however, talking to its lawyers and would take action to protect
itself against libel and slander, he added.
</TEXT>
