<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / Howard favours Sunday opening
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HOWARD, home secretary, yesterday came down firmly in favour of
deregulating Sunday shop opening hours, saying that he did not believe any
other alternative would work.
Mr Howard said, however, that MPs would still be given a choice of four
options for reforming Britain's widely-discredited Sunday trading laws and
hinted that he was prepared to listen to arguments for a compromise
solution. Speaking on BBC Television, Mr Howard made clear his preference
for extending the Conservatives' free-market economics to the high street.
The Home Office will publish a draft Sunday trading bill before the Commons
recess which starts at the end of next month. The four choices are:
Total deregulation with shops able to open on Sundays like any other day.
Partial deregulation with larger shops restricted to six hours opening and
smaller shops totally deregulated.
Limiting opening to convenience stores and sales of emergency supplies.
A complex compromise that would allow all shops to open on the four Sundays
before Christmas but only certain categories of shops to open on other
Sundays.
