<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / BSI chief resigns after rift on policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL SANDERSON, first chief executive of the British Standards
Institute, has resigned unexpectedly after 18 months, Charles Batchelor
writes. The BSI co-ordinates the writing of standards for industry.
Mr Sanderson's resignation, which took effect on June 1 but has only now
become known, followed what the BSI called 'a deep disagreement with the
board on important matters of policy and management'.
He joined BSI from AWD Bedford Trucks, where he had been managing director.
'I am very sad,' he said. 'It was a wonderful job. I think we were making
significant progress.'
Mr Sanderson, who is now 49, was appointed in November 1991 to spearhead the
modernisation of the organisation. The BSI said at the time that his task
would be to 'lead a major programme of cultural change'. His departure
leaves the organisation without a chief executive at a time of growing
interest in the issue of standards.
BS5750, a quality systems standard, has become the focus of growing
controversy with criticism from small businesses that it is unduly
bureaucratic.
Neither the BSI nor Mr Sanderson would comment further on the reasons for
his departure.
</TEXT>
