<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / Aintree rejects National criticism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AINTREE RACECOURSE officials yesterday rejected criticisms by an inquiry
into the false starts at the Grand National in April, but said starting
procedures would be changed for next year's race.
The world's most popular steeplechase, watched by 50,000 on-course
spectators and millions of television viewers worldwide, had to be abandoned
after two false starts.
The inquiry, headed by Mr Justice Connell, a member of the Jockey Club,
horseracing's ruling body, yesterday strongly criticised the 'grey gate'
starting system - a tape stretched across the 65-yard width of the course -
as outdated and inadequate. It said the Aintree executive and the Jockey
Club should have replaced it.
Captain Keith Brown, the race starter, was criticised for allowing the
horses to line up too close to the tape. Each false start was declared after
horses broke the tape and became entangled in it.
Failure to recall 30 jockeys who continued to race after the second false
start was due to Mr Ken Evans, the recall man stationed down the course, the
report said.
Although it would be 'unfair and unrealistic' for Mr Evans to carry the sole
blame for the affair, he was positioned too near the starting gate and had
failed to wave a red flag to signal the false starts, the report said.
Mr Charles Barnett, Aintree's managing director, said changes would be
introduced after the Jockey Club's inquiry into starting systems reported
later this summer.
However, he rejected any responsibility for the pro-cedures criticised by
the inquiry. The 'grey gate' system was approved by the Jockey Club and had
operated successfully in pre-race tests, he said.
Mr Barnett said the inquiry's comments on Mr Evans, who was 'under the
direct control of the starter', were unfair. There was no evidence to
contradict his claim that he raised his recall flag after both false starts.
The stewards of the Jockey Club will study the report today before deciding
whether to initiate a disciplinary inquiry.
The Jockey Club has wide-ranging powers which include imposing fines on both
Mr Evans and Aintree racecourse.
</TEXT>
