<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / Redwood puts Thatcherite zeal on hold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN REDWOOD, the rightwing Welsh secretary, made clear at the weekend
his opposition to income-tax increases and excessive public-spending cuts as
he tried to reassure the principality that nothing would be put in the way
of economic recovery.
At the Welsh Conservative party conference in Llangollen he signalled in his
first speech as Welsh secretary that his Thatcherite economics and
privatisation zeal have been put on hold.
His comments highlighted the reservations in the government about the large
public-spending cuts urged by some Tory MPs. It lined Mr Redwood up as a
cabinet ally of Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, who has set economic
recovery as his 'first aim'.
Mr Redwood said that under his leadership the Welsh Office would be
committed to 'putting the search for work and investment at the top of the
agenda'. The Welsh secretary, a member of the Thatcherite No Turning Back
Group, made only one reference to privatisation - a boast that as a junior
trade and industry minister he had not sold Cardiff-based Companies House.
He told Welsh Tories: 'Recovery is the best way of stopping the deficit. We
should never put tackling the deficit above the needs of the elderly, the
disabled, the disadvantaged, who cannot compete in the marketplace.'
He said the Tory 1992 election manifesto had opposed income-tax increases.
'It was right then. It's right today.'
On the government's public spending review, he said: 'Some urge us to make
deep cuts in public spending now. They fear otherwise markets will have
their way and lose confidence. Yet markets will take confidence if recovery
continues and strengthens.'
Mr Redwood, under attack from political opponents and under suspicion from
some Welsh Tories for his firmly English roots, said there 'has always been
a welcome in the hillsides for Englishman in love with the Welsh rhythms and
landscape'.
He would be supporting Wales in football and Glamorgan at cricket. He even
made an enthusiastic stab at singing the Welsh national anthem. Speaking to
journalists, Mr Redwood said Mr John Major and Mr Clarke were right to
review all parts of public spending, but he said he had set out 'the
strategy'.
He hinted that he saw public-spending savings coming more from controlling
pay.
</TEXT>
