<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 93 / Germany's SPD picks Scharping to be new leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Rudolf Scharping, the 45-year-old premier of the west German state of the
Rhineland-Palatinate, emerged yesterday as the certain new leader of the
opposition Social Democrats, and the man most likely to challenge Chancellor
Helmut Kohl for his job in next year's elections.
He won a clear victory over his two rivals in yesterday's unprecedented
'primary' vote of party members. Mr Scharping will be formally proposed as
national chairman today at the national executive meeting of the SPD and his
position needs to be confirmed at a party conference on June 25.
The vote reflects hesitant steps by the troubled opposition towards the
centre ground of German politics, and amounts to a setback for the more
radical policies espoused by Mr Scharping's rivals.
His victory will be greeted with relief by the party establishment, who
feared the ambition of his main rival, Mr Gerhard Schroder, the Lower Saxony
premier. Mr Scharping - a life-long politician, first as a research
assistant and then serving in his state parliament - is seen as a safe pair
of hands, likely to follow the cautious centrism of Mr Bjorn Engholm, the
former party chairman, who resigned last month following a political scandal
in his home state of Schleswig-Holstein.
Mr Scharping will, however, have a huge task to raise his political profile
in less than 18 months before the next election, against the dominant, if
unpopular, figure of Mr Kohl. According to an opinion poll published
yesterday by the ntv television station, 52 per cent of those asked felt
unable to say if he was doing a good or bad job because they did not know
him.
He was described at the weekend by Mr Otto Lambsdorff, the retiring leader
of the Free Democratic party, as 'mouse grey'.
More than 70 per cent of voters - including 33 per cent of SPD supporters -
believe that Mr Kohl's Christian Democratic Union will win the next election
and decide the chancellor, although the SPD and CDU are roughly equal in
electoral support.
Mr Schroder, 49, who started the leadership campaign as favourite, and Ms
Heidemarie Wieczoreck-Zeul, 50, who sought to consolidate the left-wing vote
in the party, both conceded defeat last night and threw their weight behind
Mr Scharping.
Mr Schroder had fought on the basis of a firm commitment to a coalition with
the Green party at next year's elections, which almost certainly cost him
votes, whereas Mr Scharping has left all his options open.
The victor won a majority in all the most populous German states, with the
exception of Lower Saxony, and in all the states of eastern Germany, except
Berlin. He emerged with 197,000 votes, or 40.3 per cent, against 162,000
(33.2 per cent) for Mr Schroder and nearly 130,000 (26.5 per cent) for Ms
Wieczoreck-Zeul.
</TEXT>
