<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 93 / Finance and the Family: Directors' Transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By COLIN ROGERS, The Inside Track
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERPETUAL has proved itself capable of producing consistently above-average
performance from its fund management business and its shares have reflected
this success. They have outperformed the market by almost 280 per cent over
the past year, so it is hardly surprising that directors see this as an
opportunity to take profits. Robert Yerbury has sold 20,000 at 470p, leaving
him with just 53,000. By far the largest shareholder on the board is
chairman Martyn Arbib, with more than 18.5m.
Shares in Yorkshire Chemicals appear to have regained institutional favour
after dropping as low as 250p last September. Philip Lowe, the chairman and
managing director, has sold 100,000 at 385p, reducing his holding to 74,000.
The company completed a 1-for-5 rights issue in March, raising around Pounds
24m.
International Food Machinery came to the market last December and has
performed well. Announcing results for 1992, the board indicated that
first-quarter performance was satisfactory and that it was confident about
the rest of the year. Managing director John Holroyd and Sean Kelly have
sold 80,000 and 50,000 shares respectively at 68p.
