<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Osborne &amp; Little better than expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Osborne &amp; Little rose by 16p to 113p yesterday after the wallpaper
and furnishing fabrics group reported better than expected trading results
and announced a dividend increase.
However, a Pounds 1.2m exceptional loss on the sale in August of Fardis, its
French subsidiary, meant the group suffered a pre-tax loss of Pounds 98,000
in the year to March 31, compared with a profit of Pounds 855,000 the
previous year.
There was a loss of 8.12p per share (7.83p earnings) but Sir Peter Osborne,
chairman, said that the group's stronger balance sheet and improved trading
results justified a 10.6 per cent increase in the final dividend to 2.6p
(2.35p) per share, making a 4.6p (4.35p) total.
Group turnover fell to Pounds 17.9m (Pounds 19.1m), including Pounds 1.83m
(Pounds 5.65m) from discontinued operations, but the contribution from
continuing operations grew by 19 per cent.
Operating profits slipped slightly to Pounds 1.32m (Pounds 1.38m) but were
ahead by 16 per cent to Pounds 1.2m (Pounds 1.04m) on a continuing
operations basis. Net interest payable fell to Pounds 224,000 (Pounds
525,000).
The group's expanding US operations boosted sales by 29 per cent which Sir
Peter described as 'an exceptional result against the background of a very
depressed home furnishings market.'
In the UK, however, where the group closed its Edinburgh showroom, sales
only increased by 4 per cent.
